ion in Russia -- t12. Indigenous Hospitality and Tourism: Past Trajectories and New Beginnings -- tPart 4: Tourism Negotiating Sami Traditions -- t13. What Does the Sieidi Do? Tourism as a Part of a Continued Tradition? -- t14. Sami Tourism in Northern Norway: Indigenous Spirituality and Processes of Cultural Branding -- t15. Respect in the Girdnu: The Sami Verdde Institution and Tourism in Northern Norway -- tPart 5: Epilogue -- t16. Toward a De-Essentializing of Indigenous Tourism? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first book to exclusively address tourism and indigenous peoples in the circumpolar North. It examines how tourism in indigenous communities is influenced by academic and political discourses, and how these communities are influenced by tourism. The volume focuses on the ambivalence relating to tourism as a modern force within ethnic groups who are concerned with maintaining indigenous roots and traditional practices. It seeks to challenge stereotypical understandings of indigenousness and indigeneity and considers conflicting imaginaries of the Arctic and Arctic indigenous tourism. The book contains case studies from Canada, Greenland, Norway, Sweden, Finland and Russia and will be of interest to postgraduate students and researchers of tourism, geography, sociology, cultural studies and anthropology.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArctic peoples. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszArctic regions. 0aTourismzArctic regions. 4aArctic regions. 4aGEOGRAPHY. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aArctic.  aIndigeneity.  aIndigenous tourism.  aPolar tourism.  aPolar.  aTourism development.  aindigenous communities.  aindigenous